 judge research such as Saenger’s against idealized practices, Contested Medicine eschews such an approach and considers why Saenger’s peers and later critics had so much difficulty reaching an unambiguous ethical assessment. Kutcher’s engaging investigation offers an approach to clinical ethics and research imperatives that lays bare many of the conflicts and tensions of the postwar period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCancerxResearchxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aCancerxResearchzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aClinical trialsxMoral and ethical aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aClinical trialsxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aHuman experimentation in medicinexHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aHuman experimentation in medicinezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMedicine, MilitaryxResearchxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aMedicine, MilitaryxResearchzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRadiationxPhysiological effectxResearchxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aRadiationxPhysiological effectxResearchzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ahuman experiments, medicine, science, ethics, biology, cancer, treatment, radiation, eugene saenger, radiologist, university of cincinnati, department defense, soldiers, military, nuclear war, combat effectiveness, battlefield, medical trials, government, childhood leukemia, research, peer review, knowledge, nonfiction, trust, authority.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022646531940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226465333423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226465333/original  a978-3-11-